North Sea wind farms supply a good 21 percent more electricity
In the first six months of the year, the wind power stations on the German North Sea have fed electricity into the network 11,51 hours.
This is a good 21 percent more than in the same period of the previous year, announced the network operator Tennet in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for the transfer of the North Sea electricity to the mainland and the line through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of Tennet's grid area, have fed in a further 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, the wind electricity from North and Baltic Sea comes to 13.73 TWh, compared to good 11,64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea thus accounts for almost 19 percent of the total wind power in Germany; this is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms provide higher production capacities
In addition to wind conditions, the increased contribution of offshore wind energy results from higher generation capacities, as new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1270 wind power stations in the North Sea all run at the same time with full power, they could generate electricity 6,7 gigawatt.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this; according to Tennet, it is 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it should rise at 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we are investing 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore grid connections," said Tim Meyerjürgens, Managing Director of Tennet.
In reality, wind farms can not exploit their capacity at sea, but reach about 40%.
The record day so far this year is 2 January, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce about 2.5 to 3.0 Gigawatt electricity, which corresponds to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply almost seven million households with electricity.
