The song "Albatross," composed by Green, summed the group in the winter of 1968 / 69 the first number 1 hit and catapulted it to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green could not cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He commented on the life between music and searching later in an interview: "The worst thing happened to me in life is drugs - the best to land a number 1 hit."
Towards the end of the decade, Green achieved a surprising success in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac pigs this without him in new formation on a success wave.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not win a bigger comeback until he restarted with a group of friendly musicians in 1996.
The British "Daily Telegraph" spoke at the time of a rock star returning to Earth.
Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group, until the band released in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his soft sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
